A 51 - residue region from the conserved C - terminal region of <p1  pair=12 >  <p1  pair=13 >  <p1  pair=14 >  <prot>  TBP </prot>  </p1>  </p1>  </p1>  , previously shown to be the binding site for the viral activator protein <p2  pair=12 >  <prot>  E1A </prot>  </p2>  , interacts with <p2  pair=13 >  <prot>  c - Fos </prot>  </p2>  and <p2  pair=14 >  <prot>  c - Jun </prot>  </p2>  proteins .
We propose that <p1  pair=15 >  <prot>  c - Fos </prot>  </p1>  and <p1  pair=16 >  <prot>  c - Jun </prot>  </p1>  proteins function as transcriptional activators , in part by recruiting <p2  pair=15 >  <p2  pair=16 >  <prot>  TBP </prot>  </p2>  </p2>  to form complexes to initiate RNA synthesis .
